<section id="limitations" class="paper-col py-10">
  <p class="section-num">6 &middot; Limitations &amp; Future Work</p>
  <h2>Honest Boundaries</h2>

  <h3>6.1 Synthetic Data</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The training corpus and seeded <code>Auth_Rate_Stats</code> table are synthetic, parameterised
    from publicly known interchange tiers and plausible authorization patterns. The model has
    therefore not been validated against real settlement invoices or live issuer responses.
    Deploying to production would require a back&#8209;tested model trained on at least one
    quarter of actual transaction data, with calibration adjustments per region.
  </p>

  <h3>6.2 No Online Feedback Loop</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    A production system would update <code>Auth_Rate_Stats</code> continuously from observed
    authorization outcomes (EventBridge &rarr; SQS &rarr; stats&#8209;updater Lambda). This was
    deliberately omitted to keep the academic focus on the routing decision itself. The
    consequence is that the agent's auth&#8209;rate inputs cannot adapt to scheme&#8209;side
    behaviour changes (e.g.&nbsp;new fraud heuristics) until the table is manually re&#8209;seeded.
  </p>

  <h3>6.3 Single Language Model Evaluated</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    Only Claude Sonnet&nbsp;4.6 was evaluated. A rigorous comparison would benchmark at least
    Haiku&nbsp;4.5 (cost/latency trade&#8209;off), Opus&nbsp;4.7 (reasoning ceiling), and at
    least one non&#8209;Anthropic model (e.g.&nbsp;Llama&nbsp;3.1 405B via Bedrock) on the same
    fixed scenario set with a held&#8209;out evaluation harness. Output validity, JSON&#8209;schema
    adherence, and reasoning&#8209;trace quality should all be measured.
  </p>

  <h3>6.4 No Live Scheme Connectivity</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    <code>MockSchemeGateway</code> stands in for real scheme processors (VisaNet, Banknet, etc.).
    The routing decision is the contribution; integration with the scheme's authorization API
    is mechanical but out of scope.
  </p>

  <h3>6.5 Limited BIN &amp; MCC Vocabulary</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The BIN table contains ~17 representative prefixes covering FR / US / DE / CN. The ML model
    recognises 10 ISO countries and 10 MCCs. Both are sufficient for the demo scenarios but
    would need expansion to the full BIN universe (~half a million prefixes) and the full ISO
    MCC list before any production assessment.
  </p>

  <h3>6.6 Cost Considerations</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    At Bedrock pricing for Sonnet&nbsp;4.6, each decision consumes roughly 2&ndash;4&thinsp;K
    input tokens (system prompt + tool schemas + tool results) and 200&ndash;600 output tokens.
    At &asymp;$0.003&ndash;$0.015 per decision, an LLM&#8209;in&#8209;the&#8209;loop architecture
    is viable for low&#8209;volume / high&#8209;value flows but uneconomic for typical card
    transaction volumes. A two&#8209;tier design (rule engine for &gt;99&thinsp;% of traffic,
    LLM for ambiguous dual&#8209;brand cases) is a natural next step.
  </p>

  <h3>6.7 Bedrock Onboarding Friction</h3>
  <p class="mb-4">
    During development we encountered a stuck Anthropic use&#8209;case approval state on the
    target AWS account, causing Bedrock to return <code>ThrottlingException</code> with a
    misleading "too many tokens per day" message despite zero invocations. This is a known
    operational hazard and an argument for production systems to maintain an explicit
    fallback model (e.g.&nbsp;a cheaper non&#8209;Anthropic Bedrock model) for resilience.
  </p>
</section>
